It hasn't been "debunked" officially, but there are lots of sources showing that irresponsible vaping can be dangerous as hell, while still not as dangerous as smoking.
The classic one is that burning vegetable glycerin can generate formaldehyde, but it requires you to use your vape in a way that it's not intended and with today's technology is actually very difficult to do accidentally, so it's kinda like saying reading a book is dangerous because you could give yourself a papercut and bleed out.

Which outlines an entirely new problem, which is normies and kids trying to vape without knowing enough ins and outs of it as a hobby. It's not nearly as simple as jamming a paper tube into your mouth and lighting it on fire, you're handling a device that requires a little bit of understanding to use properly and a lot of understanding to use to its full potential.
